    <!-- WHY ADULTS SPECIFICALLY -->
    <h2 id="why-adults">Why Adult Elderberry Is a Different Conversation</h2>

    <p>Most elderberry marketing speaks generically about "immune support," but the right elderberry strategy for an adult is meaningfully different from a child's. Adults face cold-season immune challenges that pediatric formulations are not designed for: workplace exposure to coworkers' infections, sleep debt that impairs T-cell function, age-related immune decline (immunosenescence) that begins in the 30s, and the polypharmacy common in adult life that introduces drug interaction concerns. Adult elderberry products address these realities with higher extract concentrations, adult-strength immune cofactors, and ingredient profiles calibrated for adult body weight.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">2 days</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">shorter cold duration in adults taking elderberry. A 2019 meta-analysis of 4 RCTs in <em>Complementary Therapies in Medicine</em> found that <strong>elderberry significantly reduced the duration and severity of upper respiratory infections</strong> compared to placebo — with the greatest benefit when supplementation began within 48 hours of symptom onset.</p>
    </div>

    <p>For adult buyers, three decisions matter more than the brand: <strong>the right extract concentration</strong> (100-200mg of standardized sambucus extract per serving for adults, vs 50-100mg for kids), <strong>the right cofactor stack</strong> (whether the formula includes vitamin C and zinc at adult-clinical doses), and <strong>the right verification</strong> (TRU-ID, USP, or similar third-party identity confirmation given the documented adulteration in the herbal supplement market).</p>

    <!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
    <h2 id="how-it-works">How Elderberry Actually Works in the Adult Immune System</h2>

    <p>Elderberry (Sambucus nigra) has been used medicinally for centuries, but modern clinical research has validated its immune-supporting properties through rigorous randomized controlled trials. The black elderberry fruit contains exceptionally high concentrations of anthocyanins (specifically cyanidin-3-glucoside and cyanidin-3-sambubioside), flavonoids, and phenolic acids that demonstrate antiviral and immunomodulatory activity in human studies. The molecular mechanism operates through two complementary pathways:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Viral Entry Blockade</strong>
        <p>Elderberry anthocyanins bind to H1N1 surface proteins of influenza viruses, physically preventing attachment to host cell receptors. This is most effective early in infection before viral replication peaks — the reason elderberry timing matters more than dose.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Cytokine Activation</strong>
        <p>Elderberry increases production of IL-1 beta, IL-6, and TNF-alpha — inflammatory cytokines that recruit and activate immune cells during active infections. This amplifies the body's natural immune response in the critical first 48-72 hours.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Antioxidant Protection</strong>
        <p>Anthocyanins are potent antioxidants that neutralize free radicals generated during the immune response. This protects healthy tissues from collateral oxidative damage while the immune system fights infection.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Faster Recovery</strong>
        <p>Clinical trials show adults taking elderberry at symptom onset recover 2 days faster with reduced symptom severity. The benefit is most pronounced for influenza and common cold when supplementation begins within the first 48 hours.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial published in <em>Nutrients</em> found that <strong>elderberry supplementation reduced cold duration by 33% and symptom severity by 36%</strong> in air travelers — a population with elevated infection risk due to cabin air recirculation and close-proximity seating. The study used standardized elderberry extract at adult-clinical doses.</p>
      <cite>Tiralongo et al. — Nutrients (2016)</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- DOSING -->
    <h2 id="dosing">Adult Elderberry Dosing: Prevention vs Active Symptoms</h2>

    <p>Elderberry dosing for adults differs based on intent. Prevention dosing during cold and flu season uses lower daily amounts to maintain steady-state anthocyanin levels. Acute dosing during active symptoms uses higher amounts in shorter windows to maximize antiviral activity at the moment it matters most. The table below summarizes evidence-based dosing for adults across both scenarios:</p>

    <div class="ctbl">
      <p class="ctbl-hint">&larr; Scroll horizontally if needed &rarr;</p>
      <div class="ctbl-scroll">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Scenario</th>
              <th>Standardized Extract</th>
              <th>Raw Berry Equivalent</th>
              <th>Frequency</th>
              <th>Duration</th>
            </tr>
