    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Elderberry Gummies for Adults</h2>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Do elderberry gummies actually work for adults?</summary>
      <p>A 2019 meta-analysis of four randomized controlled trials in Complementary Therapies in Medicine found elderberry significantly reduced cold duration by 2 days and severity, with the greatest benefit when started within 48 hours of symptom onset. The active anthocyanins block viral entry and stimulate cytokine-mediated immune response.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How much elderberry should adults take daily?</summary>
      <p>For prevention during cold-season: 100-200mg standardized extract once daily (equivalent to 500-1,000mg raw berry). For active symptoms: 200-400mg two to four times daily for 3-5 days, beginning within 48 hours of first symptoms. Always follow product-specific dosing — extract concentrations vary across brands.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What is the difference between elderberry for kids and adults?</summary>
      <p>Adult formulas have higher extract concentrations (100-200mg vs 50-100mg), adult-clinical cofactor doses (zinc 7.5-15mg vs 2.5-5mg, vitamin C 60-90mg), and may include ingredients like echinacea or propolis that are excluded from children's formulas. Adults using kids' formulas typically need to double the serving and may end up paying more.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Can I take elderberry gummies every day?</summary>
      <p>Daily use during cold-and-flu season (October-April) is supported by clinical trials of up to 5 months of continuous use. Year-round use is less well-studied — some practitioners recommend seasonal cycling. Prolonged immune stimulation beyond 5 months has limited safety data, particularly in adults with autoimmune conditions.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Should I take elderberry with vitamin C and zinc?</summary>
      <p>Yes, the combination is well-supported by clinical evidence. Each ingredient targets a different immune pathway: elderberry blocks viral entry plus stimulates cytokines, vitamin C supports neutrophil function and acts as an antioxidant, zinc inhibits viral replication and supports T-cell maturation. Many premium formulas combine all three; see our triple-stack rankings.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Are elderberry gummies safe for adults with autoimmune conditions?</summary>
      <p>Caution required. Elderberry stimulates cytokines (IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha), which could theoretically worsen conditions where the immune system is already overactive — rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, MS, Crohn's. No direct evidence of harm, but the theoretical mechanism warrants medical consultation. Adults on immunosuppressant medications should avoid elderberry entirely.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>When is the best time to take elderberry as an adult?</summary>
      <p>For prevention: once daily with breakfast for steady-state anthocyanin levels and consistent adherence. For acute symptoms: begin within 48 hours of first symptoms — clinical trials show this window produces the largest reduction in cold duration. Keep a bottle accessible at home and work so you can begin immediately when illness starts.</p>
    </details>

